{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XBEqjV76A1iDrSgdKqrLxw","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 8.5: Rust Dockerfile template generation\n     2→\n     3→Status: review\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As a developer deploying a Rust project,\n    10→I want codeharness to generate a multi-stage Dockerfile,\n    11→so that I get a minimal runtime image with just the compiled binary.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→1. **AC1:** Given a Rust project (stack = `'rust'`) without a Dockerfile, when `generateDockerfileTemplate('/project', 'rust')` is called, then it writes a Dockerfile and returns `ok({ path: '/project/Dockerfile', stack: 'rust' })` — NOT `'generic'` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→2. **AC2:** Given the generated Rust Dockerfile content, when inspected, then it contains a multi-stage build: a `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder` stage and a `FROM debian:bookworm-slim` runtime stage <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→3. **AC3:** Given the generated Rust Dockerfile content, when inspected, then the builder stage includes `cargo build --release` and the runtime stage uses `COPY --from=builder` to copy the compiled binary <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→4. **AC4:** Given the generated Rust Dockerfile content, when inspected, then the runtime stage installs `curl` and `jq` via `apt-get install`, runs as a non-root user, and includes `rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*` cache cleanup <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→5. **AC5:** Given a Rust project with an existing Dockerfile, when `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called, then it returns `fail('Dockerfile already exists')` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→6. **AC6:** Given the generated Rust Dockerfile, when `validateDockerfile()` is called against it, then it passes all 6 rule categories with zero gaps <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→7. **AC7:** Given `codeharness init` runs on a Rust project without a Dockerfile, when the Dockerfile template generation phase executes, then it generates a Rust-specific Dockerfile (not generic) <!-- verification: integration-required -->\n    22→\n    23→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    24→\n    25→- [x] Task 1: Add `rustTemplate()` function to `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` (AC: #2, #3, #4)\n    26→  - [x]1.1 Create `rustTemplate(): string` returning a multi-stage Dockerfile string\n    27→  - [x]1.2 Builder stage: `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder`, `WORKDIR /build`, `COPY . .`, `RUN cargo build --release`\n    28→  - [x]1.3 Runtime stage: `FROM debian:bookworm-slim`, `apt-get install curl jq`, `rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`, `COPY --from=builder /build/target/release/myapp /usr/local/bin/myapp`, `USER nobody`, `WORKDIR /workspace`\n    29→  - [x]1.4 Include inline section comments matching existing template style\n    30→- [x] Task 2: Add `'rust'` branch to `generateDockerfileTemplate()` (AC: #1)\n    31→  - [x]2.1 In the if/else chain (lines 99-108), add `else if (stack === 'rust')` BEFORE the generic fallthrough\n    32→  - [x]2.2 Set `content = rustTemplate()` and `resolvedStack = 'rust'`\n    33→- [x] Task 3: Update existing test that asserts `'rust'` maps to `'generic'` (AC: #1)\n    34→  - [x]3.1 In `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts` line 167, the test `'generates generic Dockerfile when stack is unknown'` passes `'rust'` and expects `stack: 'generic'` — this MUST change\n    35→  - [x]3.2 Replace `'rust'` in that test with a different unknown stack (e.g., `'java'`) so the generic fallthrough test still works\n    36→- [x] Task 4: Add new `describe('generateDockerfileTemplate — rust')` test block (AC: #1, #2, #3, #4)\n    37→  - [x]4.1 Test: returns `stack: 'rust'` and correct path\n    38→  - [x]4.2 Test: contains `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder` and `FROM debian:bookworm-slim`\n    39→  - [x]4.3 Test: includes `cargo build --release` in builder stage\n    40→  - [x]4.4 Test: includes `COPY --from=builder` to copy compiled binary\n    41→  - [x]4.5 Test: includes `curl` and `jq` verification tools\n    42→  - [x]4.6 Test: includes `USER nobody` for non-root execution\n    43→  - [x]4.7 Test: includes apt cache cleanup (`rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`)\n    44→  - [x]4.8 Test: includes inline section comments (`# Build`, `# System utilities`, `# Install`, `# Run as non-root`)\n    45→- [x] Task 5: Add Rust template to validation compliance tests (AC: #6)\n    46→  - [x]5.1 In the `describe('generated Dockerfiles pass validateDockerfile()')` block (line 273), add a `'rust template passes all 6 rule categories'` test\n    47→  - [x]5.2 Generate Rust template, feed content to `validateDockerfile()` via mocked `readFileSync`, assert `passed: true` and `gaps: []`\n    48→- [x] Task 6: Run full test suite — zero regressions\n    49→\n    50→## Dev Notes\n    51→\n    52→### Current Code Structure\n    53→\n    54→`src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` (119 lines) has three template functions and one generator:\n    55→- `nodejsTemplate()` L21 → single-stage, `FROM node:22-slim`, `npm install -g` from tarball\n    56→- `pythonTemplate()` L41 → single-stage, `FROM python:3.12-slim`, `pip install` from wheel\n    57→- `genericTemplate()` L59 → single-stage, `FROM node:22-slim`, placeholder\n    58→- `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir, stack)` L82 → if/else chain: `'nodejs'` → `'python'` → else (generic)\n    59→\n    60→Currently `'rust'` falls through to the `else` branch and produces a generic Dockerfile. After this story, it gets its own dedicated multi-stage template.\n    61→\n    62→### Multi-Stage Build — Why Different\n    63→\n    64→Existing templates (nodejs, python) are single-stage because they install from pre-built artifacts (tarball, wheel). Rust compiles from source to a static binary — the builder stage is needed to compile, then only the binary is copied to a minimal runtime image. This is standard Rust Docker practice.\n    65→\n    66→### Validator Compatibility Analysis (AC6)\n    67→\n    68→The 6 rule categories in `dockerfile-validator.ts` and how the Rust template passes:\n    69→\n    70→1. **pinned-from** (L71): Checks all `FROM` lines for version tags. Both `rust:1.82-slim` and `debian:bookworm-slim` have version tags. **PASSES.**\n    71→2. **binary-on-path** (L85): Regex `/COPY\\s+--from=/i` at L90 matches `COPY --from=builder ...`. **PASSES.**\n    72→3. **verification-tools** (L97): Looks for `curl` and `jq` on `apt-get install` lines. **PASSES.**\n    73→4. **no-source-copy** (L116): Regex checks for `COPY src/`, `COPY lib/`, `COPY test/`. **CRITICAL**: The builder stage uses `COPY . .` which does NOT match these patterns. Do NOT use `COPY src/ src/` in the builder stage — it triggers the validator. Use `COPY . .` instead. **PASSES with `COPY . .`.**\n    74→5. **non-root-user** (L129): Checks for `USER` instruction with non-root user. `USER nobody` qualifies. **PASSES.**\n    75→6. **cache-cleanup** (L144): Checks for `rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/`. **PASSES.**\n    76→\n    77→### Template Content\n    78→\n    79→```dockerfile\n    80→# === Builder stage ===\n    81→FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder\n    82→\n    83→WORKDIR /build\n    84→\n    85→# Copy project files\n    86→COPY . .\n    87→\n    88→# Build release binary\n    89→RUN cargo build --release\n    90→\n    91→# === Runtime stage ===\n    92→FROM debian:bookworm-slim\n    93→\n    94→# System utilities for verification\n    95→RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends curl jq && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n    96→\n    97→# Install compiled binary from builder (update 'myapp' to your binary name)\n    98→COPY --from=builder /build/target/release/myapp /usr/local/bin/myapp\n    99→\n   100→# Run as non-root user\n   101→USER nobody\n   102→\n   103→WORKDIR /workspace\n   104→```\n   105→\n   106→The binary name `myapp` is a placeholder — same approach as `genericTemplate()` using `placeholder`. Users edit it. Do NOT attempt to read `Cargo.toml` at generation time.\n   107→\n   108→### Breaking Test at Line 167\n   109→\n   110→The existing test at line 164-172:\n   111→```typescript\n   112→it('generates generic Dockerfile when stack is unknown', () => {\n   113→    mockExistsSync.mockReturnValue(false);\n   114→    const r = generateDockerfileTemplate('/project', 'rust');\n   115→    expect(r.success).toBe(true);\n   116→    if (r.success) {\n   117→      expect(r.data.stack).toBe('generic');\n   118→    }\n   119→  });\n   120→```\n   121→\n   122→This test uses `'rust'` as the \"unknown stack\" example. After adding the Rust branch, this breaks. **Fix**: Replace `'rust'` with `'java'` (or any other unsupported stack) in this test, and create a separate Rust-specific test block.\n   123→\n   124→### init-project.ts Integration (AC7)\n   125→\n   126→`init-project.ts` line 78 already calls `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir, stack)`. When `detectStack()` returns `'rust'`, the generator now produces the Rust template. No changes to `init-project.ts` needed.\n   127→\n   128→### Architecture Constraints\n   129→\n   130→- **<300 line limit**: Adding ~30 lines to 119-line file = ~149 lines. Safe.\n   131→- **No new npm dependencies**: Pure string template.\n   132→- **NFR5**: Uses existing `Result<T>`, `DockerfileTemplateResult` type. No type changes.\n   133→\n   134→### Project Structure Notes\n   135→\n   136→Files to modify:\n   137→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` — add `rustTemplate()` + branch\n   138→- `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts` — update generic test, add rust test block + validation test\n   139→\n   140→Files for reference only (do NOT modify):\n   141→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts` — validator rules\n   142→- `src/modules/infra/init-project.ts` — calls generator (no changes needed)\n   143→- `src/modules/infra/index.ts` — re-exports (no changes needed)\n   144→\n   145→### References\n   146→\n   147→- [Source: src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts#L82-118 — generateDockerfileTemplate function with if/else chain]\n   148→- [Source: src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts#L21-74 — existing template functions pattern]\n   149→- [Source: src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts#L164-172 — existing test mapping rust→generic (MUST UPDATE)]\n   150→- [Source: src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts#L271-333 — validation compliance test block (ADD RUST)]\n   151→- [Source: src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts#L86-95 — checkBinaryOnPath accepts COPY --from=]\n   152→- [Source: src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts#L116-127 — checkNoSourceCopy regex (avoid COPY src/)]\n   153→- [Source: src/modules/infra/init-project.ts#L78 — generateDockerfileTemplate called during init]\n   154→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-rust-stack-support.md#FR4 — requirement]\n   155→\n   156→### Previous Story Intelligence (8-4)\n   157→\n   158→- 8-4 added cargo-tarpaulin to dependency registry. Zero regressions on ~2980 tests.\n   159→- 8-4 only touched `deps.ts` and `deps.test.ts` — no file overlap with this story.\n   160→- Mocking pattern in dockerfile-template tests uses `vi.mock('node:fs')` at top level with `vi.mocked()` — follow this exact pattern.\n   161→\n   162→### Git Intelligence\n   163→\n   164→Recent commits: 4e805b9 (8-4 verified), ebaddac (8-3 verified), d6a76bf (8-2 verified), 4c7f498 (8-1 detection).\n   165→All Rust stories so far modified: `stack-detect.ts`, `state.ts`, `coverage.ts`, `deps.ts` + tests.\n   166→This story touches only `dockerfile-template.ts` and its test — clean isolation from previous work.\n   167→\n   168→### Do NOT Duplicate\n   169→\n   170→- Story 4-2 created `dockerfile-template.ts` with nodejs/python/generic. This story EXTENDS it.\n   171→- Story 8-6 will create `templates/Dockerfile.verify.rust` (verification Dockerfile). Do NOT create verification templates here.\n   172→\n   173→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   174→## Verification Requirements\n   175→\n   176→- [ ] Showboat proof document created (`docs/exec-plans/active/8-5-rust-dockerfile-template.proof.md`)\n   177→- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence\n   178→- [ ] Test coverage meets target (100%)\n   179→\n   180→## Documentation Requirements\n   181→\n   182→- [ ] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated (list modules touched)\n   183→- [ ] Exec-plan created in `docs/exec-plans/active/8-5-rust-dockerfile-template.md`\n   184→\n   185→## Testing Requirements\n   186→\n   187→- [ ] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n   188→- [ ] Integration tests for cross-module interactions\n   189→- [ ] Coverage target: 100%\n   190→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n   191→\n   192→## Dev Agent Record\n   193→\n   194→### Agent Model Used\n   195→\n   196→Claude Opus 4.6 (1M context)\n   197→\n   198→### Debug Log References\n   199→\n   200→None.\n   201→\n   202→### Completion Notes List\n   203→\n   204→- All 6 tasks completed. 34/34 dockerfile-template tests pass.\n   205→- 1 pre-existing failure in migration.test.ts (unrelated to this story).\n   206→- Zero regressions: 2994/2995 tests pass across full suite.\n   207→\n   208→### File List\n   209→\n   210→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` — added `rustTemplate()` function and `'rust'` branch in if/else chain\n   211→- `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts` — fixed generic test (rust→java), added 8 Rust tests, added Rust validation compliance test\n   212→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01QPLvTF7hH7ZEy1LqPE8PcP","session_id":"daf25720-e009-4a3c-8a3c-df9d68d99484","uuid":"57873dca-c196-451b-b255-673f63534a67","timestamp":"2026-03-23T06:48:02.634Z"}
